#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:7
msgid "Terminal Tips"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:9
msgid "These are some tips how to get more out of Pygments on the terminal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:13
msgid "How do I determine which shell I am using?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:14
msgid "Run this command::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:16
msgid "$ echo $SHELL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:18
msgid ""
"Mine outputs  ``/usr/bin/fish``, which is the location of the executable. "
"This means my computer is using the fish shell. ``neofetch`` (or a similar "
"utility) can  also provide that information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:22
msgid "Most shells are POSIX compliant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:26
msgid "Aliases (POSIX)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:28
msgid "POSIX compliant shells includes ``bash`` and ``zsh``, and most shells."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:30
msgid ""
"Aliases allow you to call a function using a different name.  In this case "
"it calls :program:`pygmentize` by using a different name.  The simplest is "
"to make an alias called ``cath``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:34
msgid "$ alias cath=\"pygmentize\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:36
msgid ""
"The only thing is that :program:`pygmentize` does not really work like "
"``cat``. It does allow you to use a command that is similar to one use for "
"cat, displaying a file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:40
msgid ""
"Add additional flags can be added as desired.  The monokai style works well "
"for a dark background, so this is how you would add that option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:43
msgid "$ alias cath=\"pygmentize -O style=monokai\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:46
msgid ""
"Here is a version of ``less`` with syntax highlighting.  It is slightly more "
"complicated, because it uses the environment variable ``LESSOPEN`` to "
"preprocess the input file(s)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:50
msgid ""
"$ alias lessh='LESSOPEN=\"| pygmentize -O style=monokai %s\" less -M -R '"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:52
msgid ""
"These alias commands need to be added to your configuration in order to work "
"when you open a new terminal (or restart the computer)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:55
msgid "Add above commands to your configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:57
msgid ""
"``bash`` - edit either ``~/.bash_aliases`` (if it exists) or ``~/.bashrc`` "
"file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:58
msgid "``csh`` (C shell), edit  the ``~/.cshrc`` file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:59
msgid "``ksh`` (Korn shell), edit the ``~/.kshrc`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:60
msgid "``tcsh``, edit the ``~/.tcshrc`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:61
msgid "``zsh``, edit the ``~/.zshrc`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:63
msgid ""
"In order to apply the changes to the current shell environment systems: run "
"``source`` on the filename just edited::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:65
msgid "$ source [~/.filenamerc]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:69
msgid "Aliases (fish shell)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:70
msgid ""
"The above aliases for POSIX work just fine, but permanently saving an alias "
"in fish shell is a little different.  Functions are used to make permanent "
"aliases. ``funced [command]`` is used to create the function, followed by "
"``funcsave [command]`` saves the function to the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:76
msgid ""
"Running the ``funced cath``, brings up the default editor, and add the "
"following code in the function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:79
msgid ""
"function cath\n"
"        # 'cath' alias will highlight source code as cat does.\n"
"        alias cath=\"pygmentize\"\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:84
msgid ""
"Here's what the ``cath`` function looks like with an additional argument::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:86
msgid ""
"function cath\n"
"        alias cath=\"pygmentize -O style=monokai\"\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:90
msgid ""
"Note: that just like the POSIX shell you may run ``alias cath=\"pygmentize -"
"O style=monokai\"`` on the command line to test out the alias beforehand."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:93
msgid ""
"Test the ``cath`` function. To save the function run ``funcsave cath``. This "
"saves the function for future sessions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:97
msgid ""
"``funced lessh``, which is slightly more complicated, because it uses the "
"environment variable ``LESSOPEN`` to preprocess the input file(s)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:101
msgid ""
"function lessh\n"
"        LESSOPEN=\"| pygmentize -O style=native %s\" less -M -R $argv\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/terminaltips.rst:105
msgid ""
"Test the ``lessh`` function. To save the function run ``funcsave lessh``."
msgstr ""
